<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Open-Flame Dryer" class="currentChild" href="Open-Flame_Dryer">Open-Flame Dryer</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A type of <a title="Dryer" href="Dryer">dryer</a> (or <a title="Floating Dryer" href="Floating_Dryer">floating dryer</a>) used on a <a title="Web Press" href="Web_Press">web press</a> in which a heat source heats the air within an enclosed space through which the web passes to a very high temperature (often as high as 600ºF). The open-flame dryer (also called a <a title="Direct-Impingement Dryer" href="Direct-Impingement_Dryer">direct-impingement dryer</a>) is the oldest form of drying equipment. A commonly-used alternative is the <a title="High-Velocity Hot-Air Dryer" href="High-Velocity_Hot-Air_Dryer">high-velocity hot-air dryer</a>. See <a title="Dryer" href="Dryer">Dryer</a> and <a title="Web Offset Lithography: Dryers and Chill Rolls" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Web_Offset_Lithography:_Dryers_and_Chill_Rolls">Web Offset Lithography: Dryers and Chill Rolls</a>. 
</p>
